{{#partial "content" }}
    <div class="text">
        <p>The MOT Fraud Reporting service puts small files (known as ‘cookies’) onto your computer to collect information about how you browse the site.</p>
        <p>Cookies are used to:</p>
        <ul class="list-bullet">
            <li>measure how you use the service so it can be updated and improved based on your needs</li>
            <li>direct you down certain journeys to improve your experience</li>
        </ul>
        <div role="note" aria-label="Information" class="panel-indent">
            <p>The MOT Fraud Reporting service cookies aren’t used to identify you personally.</p>
        </div>
        <p>You’ll normally see a message on the site before we store a cookie on your computer.</p>
        <p>Find out more about <a rel="external" href="http://www.aboutcookies.org/">how to manage cookies.</a></p>
        <h2 class="heading-medium">How cookies are used on the MOT Fraud Reporting service</h2>
        <p>There are a number of different types of cookie used in the MOT Fraud Reporting service which allow the system to work securely and consistently. These are:</p>
        <ul class="list-bullet">
            <li>Google Analytics cookies</li>
            <li>the MOT Fraud Reporting service application cookies</li>
            <li>Imperva Incapsula cookies</li>
        </ul>
        <h3 class="heading-small">Google Analytics cookies</h3>
        <p>
            We use Google Analytics software to collect information about how you use the MOT Fraud Reporting service. We do this to help make sure the site is meeting the needs of its users and to help us make improvements.
        </p>
        <p>Google Analytics stores information about:</p>
        <ul class="list-bullet">
            <li>the pages you visit on the MOT Fraud Reporting service</li>
            <li>how long you spend on each page</li>
            <li>how you got to the site</li>
            <li>what you click on while you’re visiting the site</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Google do not collect or store your personal information (eg your name or address) so this information can’t be used to identify who you are. We don’t allow Google to use or share our analytics data.
        </p>
        <p>Google Analytics sets the following cookies:</p>
        <h4 class="heading-small">Universal Analytics</h4>
    </div>
